The Locust Years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
It is hardly surprising since the majority of Latin American countries have gone nowhere in the past twenty years.
Capital has been sold and national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing durable and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have truly been devoured by the locusts.
Over the past 20 years, the annual growth rate of GDP per capita in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global marketplace except through timid wage increases?
The economic stagnation is the fault of a bad government, not of bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more—a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush toward privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been put up for auction.
For a brief moment, the sale of capital helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues from privatization have yielded little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by national buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The inflow of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would embark on another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be in place to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma signals the third factor: incompetent policies.
Governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being questioned, and a random and even more corrupt effort at redistribution is underway.
The Peru and Venezuela have little more chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and her team, who conduct opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already started to flee—even though the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this may well prove to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate, which is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the financial result in economic terms, because where there is little savings, there is little investment—and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the prosperous 1970s of OPEC—years it did not participate in, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking vacations in Miami, perhaps permanently.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40 percent, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions favor the market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
Rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP is only half that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate in China's coastal region of about 15 percent per year, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first of all due to the massive flow of foreign direct investments and the imminent advantages of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments backtrack on reforms and the economy loses ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds flowed in, but these times are largely behind us.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political developments in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chávez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem — an Argentine presidential candidate once again — may resemble a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
